"As a result of nearly three years of meetings with the participation of business, legal and technical experts from more than eight countries, the Information Security Committee, Section of Science and Technology, American Bar Association (ABA) has developed draft Digital Signature Guidelines (‘Guidelines’) 1 - an abstract statement of principles, intended to serve as a long-term unifying foundation for digital signature law across varied legal settings either for adjudicatory use or legislative enactment. The Guidelines include definitions, general principles, and define the rights and responsibilities of certification authorities, subscribers (that is, persons to whom certificates have been issued) and relying parties (that is, persons who may use these certificates to authenticate messages but are not in privity with the certification authority). They also articulate legal expectations concerning reliance on digital signatures generally."
